    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ef45d137e9629d3fbe9c5f84997ac5ff?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 229892,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 493161,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/493161/jcomeau-ictx",
                "reputation": 38652,
                "display_name": "jcomeau_ictx",
                "accept_rate": 90
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1327377800,
            "creation_date": 1327377800,
            "body": "<p>It seems you're asking for an opinion, which will probably get flagged for closure, but meanwhile I agree, println is perfectly applicable. Debugging and info messages, however, normally are sent to System.err rather than System.out.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 8981864,
            "question_id": 8981839
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b2ee5980501f21314923f751e4740446?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 95764,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 260633,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/260633/dev",
                "reputation": 12266,
                "display_name": "Dev",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1327377802,
            "creation_date": 1327377802,
            "body": "<p>If you want people to reuse your code you will want to use a logger of some sort. If you're going to use a logger I'd recommend using <a href=\"http://www.slf4j.org/\" rel=\"nofollow\">SLF4J<\/a> instead of log4j. This will allow some downstream developer using your code to use whatever logging framework they want that implements or has a binding for the SLF4J API (log4j, java.util.logging, logback, etc).<\/p>\n\n<p>If you don't care about anyone reusing your code, and this is a standalone product, then yes it is probably overkill.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 8981865,
            "question_id": 8981839
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3fa6c233a1d109660622819caf68c3d6?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 406517,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 776084,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/776084/ranrag",
                "reputation": 49847,
                "display_name": "RanRag",
                "accept_rate": 79
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1327377958,
            "creation_date": 1327377958,
            "body": "<p>Anything that you print to System.out will go to \"standard out\",you can redirect it to a file for further analysis but that is very inflexible.<\/p>\n\n<p>You cannot filter what goes to standard out if you use System.out... everything will be printed. By using any logging framework like <a href=\"http://www.slf4j.org/\" rel=\"nofollow\">SLF4J<\/a>,<a href=\"http://commons.apache.org/logging/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Commons Logging<\/a> or you can use log4j, you can set different logging levels.<\/p>\n\n<p>Basically you don't want to see every debug message. You can set various logging level like <code>WARNING<\/code>,<code>DEBUG<\/code>, <code>INFO<\/code> with the help of a logger.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 8981877,
            "question_id": 8981839
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5a46c45ae5e044a4e63c9ed91b7b7c0a?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 26201,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 67945,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/67945/frankie",
                "reputation": 25195,
                "display_name": "Frankie",
                "accept_rate": 87
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1327582048,
            "creation_date": 1327377983,
            "body": "<p><strong>Probably is (overkill), but depends.<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>When you say that the software was made for your own development but then you released it to your group of developers you are actually saying that the software originally had a function and now has another function. Being the primary function serve you and the secondary (and final function) serve the group/community.<\/p>\n\n<p>*<strong><em>If in your group of developers there are code standards<\/strong>, and I sure hope there are, and if one of the standards is using log4j to log everything, that by all means you should go with the standards.<\/em>*<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 8981879,
            "question_id": 8981839,
            "last_edit_date": 1327582048
        }
    ],
